In his usual painstaking and meticulous approach to governance, Nasarawa State Governor, Engineer Abdullahi Sule has announced new indices for measuring the performance of his commissioners and also to ensure strict compliance to policies of financial transparency and accountability. Governor Sule made this declaration at the Executive Council Meeting which held in Government House Lafia, on Wednesday, June 24, 2020. It will be recalled that two weeks after being inaugurated as governor on May 29th 2019, Engineer Sule conducted ministerial briefings with departments and agencies from 13th June to 1st July 2019, arising from which he constituted a committee of technocrats to restructure and re- form the Nasarawa State civil service. The rationale of Engineer Abdullahi A. Sule was an urgent need to break the inertia and reform the Nasarawa State Civil Service on the basis of attracting a competent workforce, reintroduce training of civil servants and build the middle management level cadre for efficient service delivery, while stimulating fiscal discipline and transparent revenue generation on behalf of the government.
Engineer Abdullahi A. Sule wanted all the wheels, tires and parts of government to work cohesively and in perfect harmony on the basis of transparency, innovation and productivity as obtains in the private sector.
That is why on Friday, 6th September 2019, Engineer held a Stakeholders Meeting to commemorate “100 DAYS IN OFFICE” where he restated the his administration’s commitment to values of open governance and public transpar-
ency when he reaffirmed: “we owe you a duty as a responsive administration that has imbibed the principles of accountability, transparency, due process and prudent management of public resources, to give a report of our journey from time to time!”